WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.360
Alright, let's talk about a piece of assistive technology

2
00:00:02.360 --> 00:00:05.045
that is a huge blind spot for so many designers,

3
00:00:05.305 --> 00:00:06.405
screen magnification.

4
00:00:06.735 --> 00:00:08.925
We're gonna get into why it's so often overlooked

5
00:00:08.945 --> 00:00:10.645
and why that's a really big deal.

6
00:00:11.505 --> 00:00:13.235
Okay, let's just start right here

7
00:00:13.235 --> 00:00:14.755
because this quote says it all.

8
00:00:15.095 --> 00:00:17.835
Low vision is the most common visual disability.

9
00:00:18.225 --> 00:00:21.355
That means way more people are using magnification tools

10
00:00:21.385 --> 00:00:22.755
than say, screen readers.

11
00:00:23.055 --> 00:00:24.995
But for some reason we tend to think, oh,

12
00:00:25.155 --> 00:00:26.195
I checked browser zoom.

13
00:00:26.415 --> 00:00:27.595
I'm good. Today.

14
00:00:27.685 --> 00:00:30.475
We're gonna see why that assumption is fundamentally broken.

15
00:00:31.335 --> 00:00:32.555
So here's our game plan.

16
00:00:32.605 --> 00:00:34.235
We'll start with the zoom you're already used to

17
00:00:34.455 --> 00:00:36.555
and then we'll dive into the two very different

18
00:00:36.555 --> 00:00:37.715
worlds of magnification.

19
00:00:38.305 --> 00:00:40.155
From there, we'll see what it's actually like

20
00:00:40.155 --> 00:00:41.835
to browse the web through a keyhole.

21
00:00:42.095 --> 00:00:44.395
See how perfectly good designs can fall apart.

22
00:00:44.645 --> 00:00:46.515
Learn how to really test for this stuff

23
00:00:46.815 --> 00:00:48.155
and then boil it all down

24
00:00:48.175 --> 00:00:51.475
to two super simple design principles, right?

25
00:00:51.575 --> 00:00:52.875
So let's start on familiar ground.

26
00:00:53.135 --> 00:00:55.835
You know about WCAG, you test for zoom

27
00:00:55.835 --> 00:00:57.875
and reflow as part of your accessibility checklist,

28
00:00:58.095 --> 00:01:00.755
and honestly, that is a great and necessary first step.

29
00:01:01.535 --> 00:01:02.595
So you do the thing, right?

30
00:01:02.775 --> 00:01:04.035
You crank up the browser, zoom

31
00:01:04.035 --> 00:01:07.075
to 400% the content reflows into a single column,

32
00:01:07.455 --> 00:01:09.075
no horizontal scroll bar appears

33
00:01:09.215 --> 00:01:11.355
and you check the box, you are compliant.

34
00:01:11.695 --> 00:01:13.195
But here's the million dollar question.

35
00:01:13.585 --> 00:01:16.635
Does that check box actually mean a real person using

36
00:01:16.635 --> 00:01:18.235
magnification can use your site?

37
00:01:18.655 --> 00:01:20.195
The answer, as you're about to find out,

38
00:01:20.215 --> 00:01:21.835
is often a resounding no.

39
00:01:22.535 --> 00:01:26.395
And to get why that is, we first have to understand

40
00:01:26.395 --> 00:01:29.195
that magnification isn't just one thing,

41
00:01:29.545 --> 00:01:31.155
it's a whole category of tools

42
00:01:31.375 --> 00:01:32.835
and they work in completely different ways.

43
00:01:33.955 --> 00:01:36.325
This right here, this is the core concept.

44
00:01:36.505 --> 00:01:39.405
You need to get browser zoom the thing you test for.

45
00:01:39.405 --> 00:01:41.605
Compliance, literally rebuilds the page layout,

46
00:01:41.745 --> 00:01:44.685
it reflows everything but system magnification.

47
00:01:44.985 --> 00:01:46.485
It does something totally different.

48
00:01:46.655 --> 00:01:47.645
Think of it like a literal

49
00:01:47.645 --> 00:01:49.125
magnifying glass held up to your screen.

50
00:01:49.345 --> 00:01:50.925
It just makes the pixels bigger.

51
00:01:51.225 --> 00:01:52.645
The layout doesn't change at all.

52
00:01:53.065 --> 00:01:54.325
And that difference, well,

53
00:01:54.385 --> 00:01:55.965
it changes everything for the user.

54
00:01:56.885 --> 00:01:59.425
And these tools really fall into four main buckets.

55
00:01:59.605 --> 00:02:01.905
You've got the heavy duty software like Zoom text,

56
00:02:02.035 --> 00:02:04.625
which often bundles, magnification with a screen reader.

57
00:02:04.935 --> 00:02:07.265
Then you've got the tools built right into the operating

58
00:02:07.265 --> 00:02:10.745
system like Windows Magnifier or the Zoom on Mac Os.

59
00:02:10.895 --> 00:02:12.705
They're free and on every machine.

60
00:02:13.255 --> 00:02:15.345
Then there's the browser zoom, you already know.

61
00:02:15.645 --> 00:02:18.665
And of course, pinch to zoom on your phone. See a pattern.

62
00:02:19.175 --> 00:02:22.705
Most of these are pixel magnifiers, not layout reflows.

63
00:02:23.665 --> 00:02:25.045
And this brings us to the real

64
00:02:25.345 --> 00:02:26.485
aha moment of this whole thing.

65
00:02:26.905 --> 00:02:30.125
To truly understand what designing for magnification means

66
00:02:30.665 --> 00:02:32.685
you have to stop thinking about your design on

67
00:02:32.725 --> 00:02:33.805
a big beautiful monitor.

68
00:02:34.315 --> 00:02:37.045
Instead, I want you to imagine you're trying to see it

69
00:02:37.045 --> 00:02:38.605
through a tiny keyhole.

70
00:02:39.525 --> 00:02:42.515
Let's make this real. What is the lived experience?

71
00:02:42.945 --> 00:02:45.515
What does somebody using system level magnification

72
00:02:46.075 --> 00:02:47.515
actually see when they land on your page?

73
00:02:48.735 --> 00:02:51.265
Okay, let's start with a pretty common setting.

74
00:02:51.615 --> 00:02:53.025
Four times magnification.

75
00:02:53.975 --> 00:02:56.875
At this level, the user is seeing just one 16th

76
00:02:56.935 --> 00:02:58.035
of your beautiful design.

77
00:02:58.215 --> 00:03:01.645
At any given moment, the rest of the screen is just gone.

78
00:03:02.065 --> 00:03:04.525
To see anything else, they have to physically pan

79
00:03:04.525 --> 00:03:05.565
that little window around.

80
00:03:06.625 --> 00:03:08.325
Now what if they need more clarity?

81
00:03:08.695 --> 00:03:10.725
Let's push it to eight times magnification,

82
00:03:10.855 --> 00:03:12.405
which is not uncommon at all.

83
00:03:13.155 --> 00:03:17.135
At eight x their views shrinks to a staggering one 64th

84
00:03:17.195 --> 00:03:18.935
of the total screen area.

85
00:03:19.605 --> 00:03:21.335
Just pause and think about that for a second.

86
00:03:21.835 --> 00:03:23.695
How would you navigate a complex header

87
00:03:23.695 --> 00:03:25.935
or fill out a form if you could only see

88
00:03:25.935 --> 00:03:27.015
that tiny piece of it?

89
00:03:27.555 --> 00:03:30.615
So how on earth do people manage this? It's not chaos.

90
00:03:31.005 --> 00:03:32.455
They are actively Building a

91
00:03:32.455 --> 00:03:33.735
mental map of your interface.

92
00:03:34.045 --> 00:03:36.895
They're using their spatial memory, relying on things

93
00:03:36.895 --> 00:03:39.055
that are always in the same place, like your logo

94
00:03:39.195 --> 00:03:41.495
or main navigation to orient themselves.

95
00:03:42.025 --> 00:03:43.295
Their software helps By

96
00:03:43.295 --> 00:03:44.455
following the mouse or the keyboard

97
00:03:44.505 --> 00:03:46.615
Focus, but It all hinges on a layout

98
00:03:46.615 --> 00:03:48.095
that is predictable and makes sense.

99
00:03:48.875 --> 00:03:50.735
So this is where it gets painful.

100
00:03:51.745 --> 00:03:53.035
What happens when a design

101
00:03:53.035 --> 00:03:54.915
that looks amazing at a hundred percent

102
00:03:55.015 --> 00:03:58.635
and even passes that WCAG reflow test gets viewed

103
00:03:58.635 --> 00:04:00.075
through this tiny keyhole?

104
00:04:00.895 --> 00:04:03.615
Well, it breaks a lot.

105
00:04:04.645 --> 00:04:07.025
And these are the classic culprits.

106
00:04:07.205 --> 00:04:09.145
You've gotta label way over on the left

107
00:04:09.285 --> 00:04:12.745
and its input field is way on the right through a keyhole.

108
00:04:12.765 --> 00:04:14.105
The user has to pan back

109
00:04:14.225 --> 00:04:16.185
and forth trying to remember what they're supposed

110
00:04:16.185 --> 00:04:18.545
to be typing or a tool tip pops up,

111
00:04:18.605 --> 00:04:21.545
but it's outside their tiny view so they never even see it.

112
00:04:21.845 --> 00:04:25.225
And that giant trendy, sticky header at eight x zoom,

113
00:04:25.285 --> 00:04:27.465
it can eat up half of their usable screen space.

114
00:04:27.755 --> 00:04:30.665
These aren't just little annoyances, they're deal breakers.

115
00:04:31.725 --> 00:04:33.575
Okay? So that's the problem.

116
00:04:34.035 --> 00:04:37.015
It feels big, but the solution is actually pretty clear.

117
00:04:37.475 --> 00:04:40.295
You just need to stop thinking of testing as one step

118
00:04:40.595 --> 00:04:42.815
and start thinking of it as a two track approach.

119
00:04:43.845 --> 00:04:45.655
It's really this simple track.

120
00:04:45.715 --> 00:04:48.255
One is what you're already doing testing for compliance

121
00:04:48.255 --> 00:04:51.775
with browser zoom, but you need to add track two testing

122
00:04:51.995 --> 00:04:54.815
for the actual experience with system magnification.

123
00:04:55.475 --> 00:04:58.055
One is about the code, the other is about the human.

124
00:04:58.985 --> 00:05:02.725
Put it this way, browser zoom at 400% answers the question,

125
00:05:03.145 --> 00:05:06.405
can my layout technically reflow system magnification at

126
00:05:06.405 --> 00:05:07.885
four x answers the question.

127
00:05:08.425 --> 00:05:10.085
Can a person actually understand

128
00:05:10.105 --> 00:05:12.085
and navigate my layout when they can only

129
00:05:12.105 --> 00:05:13.405
see a tiny fraction of it?

130
00:05:13.795 --> 00:05:15.525
They are completely different questions

131
00:05:15.525 --> 00:05:17.365
that find completely different problems.

132
00:05:18.315 --> 00:05:21.695
So how do we design our sites to pass both of these tests?

133
00:05:22.735 --> 00:05:23.975
Honestly, it all comes down

134
00:05:23.975 --> 00:05:26.295
to two simple, powerful principles.

135
00:05:26.595 --> 00:05:28.575
If you just keep these two words in your head while you

136
00:05:28.575 --> 00:05:30.415
design, you're gonna be most of the way there.

137
00:05:31.305 --> 00:05:34.565
The first one is proximity. It's just what it sounds like.

138
00:05:34.745 --> 00:05:37.085
Things that belong together should be together visually.

139
00:05:37.585 --> 00:05:41.045
Put your labels right on top of your inputs, not miles away.

140
00:05:41.545 --> 00:05:43.765
Put error messages right next to the field with the air.

141
00:05:44.115 --> 00:05:45.565
Make sure tool tips appear right next

142
00:05:45.565 --> 00:05:46.725
to the thing you're hovering over.

143
00:05:47.385 --> 00:05:49.925
The goal is simple. Can a user see the cause

144
00:05:50.025 --> 00:05:52.525
and the effect in one single magnified view?

145
00:05:53.135 --> 00:05:55.315
And the second principle is predictability.

146
00:05:56.275 --> 00:05:58.045
Remember that mental map your user is building.

147
00:05:58.695 --> 00:06:01.525
Don't mess with it. Use consistent layouts.

148
00:06:01.675 --> 00:06:04.805
Keep your navigation in the same spot on every single page.

149
00:06:05.145 --> 00:06:07.805
And when something new appears, like a success message

150
00:06:07.905 --> 00:06:10.445
or a modal window, make sure it appears right

151
00:06:10.445 --> 00:06:13.405
where the user is already looking, not in some random corner

152
00:06:13.405 --> 00:06:16.495
of the screen they can't see. So if

153
00:06:16.495 --> 00:06:18.175
You walk away with just one thing today,

154
00:06:18.395 --> 00:06:21.375
please let it be This compliance is not experience.

155
00:06:21.755 --> 00:06:23.815
You have to start testing with the actual tools

156
00:06:23.815 --> 00:06:24.855
your users are using.

157
00:06:25.205 --> 00:06:27.935
Fire up windows, magnifier, turn on, zoom on your Mac

158
00:06:28.115 --> 00:06:30.015
and stop relying only on browser Zoom.

159
00:06:30.565 --> 00:06:32.415
I'll just leave you with this one question to take back

160
00:06:32.415 --> 00:06:33.895
to your next design review.

161
00:06:34.545 --> 00:06:36.135
Don't just ask if it's compliant.

162
00:06:36.515 --> 00:06:39.375
Ask yourself and ask your team, is it usable

163
00:06:39.375 --> 00:06:40.255
through a keyhole.
